arch:property.oc:show_val: Soil below the collapse (Locus 7) in the colonnaded corridor above the compacted surface (Locus 12)

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Full blockage, robbing out and dumping.

Locus 11 is the soft soil above the compacted surface (Locus 12) in the east of the colonnaded corridor. The soil is a fine, loose dark brown (7.5 YR 3/3) silt with few inclusions. Small amounts of pottery, bone, stucco, and glass were found. This locus likely represents a period of disuse, following the robbing-out of a large part of the floor of the colonnaded corridor. This robbing out would have occurred in Stage 5, with the full blocking of some of the rooms, including the bathroom and anteroom just to the north of the robbed-out floor area, and the accumulation of sediment could have begun almost immediately afterwards. Locus 11 is therefore phased to Stage 5, during this period of dumping and gradual abandonment of the Bath Complex.
2.97 m north south -by- 9.71 m east west.
